The sight of a guy purchasing a Ferrari with the sole intention of destroying it is undeniably perplexing. While I appreciate his content creation and understand the appeal of unique and daring stunts, I can't help but feel that a Ferrari transcends mere machinery; it is art on wheels. Art should never be treated so rashly, and this holds true for the exquisite craftsmanship and engineering that goes into creating a Ferrari. I don't harbor any ill will towards his creative endeavors, but there's a pang of regret knowing that such an exquisite piece of automotive artistry could have been cherished and celebrated rather than subjected to stunts that damage the vehicle.

Playing forza horizon in real life
So, I just gotta say, before I got disabled, I worked for the biggest used Mercedes parts places in the USA.  The biz model was: buy fancy cars that are damaged, and part them out on the internet.  So we got fancy cars in all the time, and typically they would be drivable, but would have some minor cosmetic damage, that "totalled" them, not in real life, but just in the imaginary world of automotive comprehensive insurance.  Boss had 5+ acres in a toxic waste part of town, and was a good sport about our shenanigans, as long as we worked hard, helped her out of a jam when she had rush orders, that kind of thing.  Basically as long as we were good employees, we could get a little dukes of Hazzard when we wanted.  All that is just to give my credentials when I say that your videos cause me physical pain, but it's like going to therapy or something.  I grew up poor, I started buying my own food and clothing around age 10, and got my first legit job paying taxes and all that at 13, in my country you need a special permit to work at 14, the feds really dropped the ball on protecting me, hah.  My parents made okay money, but had some major mental health issues, so I was raised kinda feral.  I sorta rebelled against my crazy parents by being super financially responsible, instead of normal kids rebelling against their responsible parents by being whacky.  So even though I'm 40, I've got this like deeply deeply engrained need to not damage expensive things, or allow others to damage them through inaction.  So yes, thank you for the free therapy from destroying expensive things, I'm too cheap, because of my childhood trauma, to spring for the real thing, which I so desperately need, lol.

It's funny to me how many misconceptions there are about Ferrari. I mean, a bunch of people on TikTok who never could afford a Ferrari are malding about the fact that Ferrari is going against people who put a bad light on their brand. Let me tell you the actual truth about Ferrari as someone who has traded with Ferraris for 15 years. First of all, the only lawsuits people have had with Ferrari have been with people who manipulated the Ferrari logo, many brands do so, especially if people change the logo to make fun of the brand or discredit them.  Furthermore, there has never been a lawsuit because someone replaced parts themselves, did some tuning, or put in some Chinese parts to change the look of their Ferrari. All they do is put you on a blacklist, meaning they won't sell you a Ferrari anymore. What's so wrong with a brand deciding not to sell their car to everyone? I mean, there are so many people waiting in line to get a Ferrari, why should they care about a meaningless person on TikTok who does clickbait and spreads false informations?  Just so you know, many car brands have a blacklist. They are just not so open about it. Bugatti, Ferrari, Lamborghini, especially Rolls Royce, hell even Mercedes won't sell to everyone if a person has been noticed multiple times in a negative way. So why are people so mad about that? Even I am on their blacklist because I am a known reseller. Do I care? No.  Actually there should be a blacklist for almost every company. That would give them legal rights to go against resellers who are abusing bots such as Nike or GPU manufacturers, thats what you all want, right?

Those green plastic containers.  When I was active duty airforce (combat comm), we'd have stacks high of those same green plastic boxes.  High quality stuff. They even have purge buttons on the side since its air tight.  The black plastic molding inside used to smell like rotten dog shit, but if you wanted to keep super expensive equipment sealed from air, water, heat and shock from being dropped from 50 feet, then those where the boxes to use.  We used to take them when we'd get new ones, but we only had lots of the two man carry ones that were big.  The smaller cases was always grabbed by the seniors.  Good shit to have tho
